I started by downloading Oracle's Virtual Box which is an opensource operating system. We can download virtual machines in it. The machines we will download are Kali Linux and Ubuntu.

We used Kali because it is an open-source operating system mainly used for penetration testing and digital forensics. 

I created the VM by downloading the extension pack of Kali, then uploaded it onto VirtualBox. Then, I started the machine and finished setting it up. 

The first command I ran on the terminal of my Kali system was (sudo apt update). It refreshes Kali's list of available software and updates.

Then I ran (sudo apt full-upgrade -y); this command downloads and installs the latest version of packages including bug fixes and security patches.

Then I was able to learn the basic commands which included:
- pwd (print working directory)
- ls (list)
- ls -la (list hidden files)
- mkdir (make directory)
- cd (change directory)
- touch (create file)
- nano (use Nano text editor)
- cat (display the contents of the file)
